{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640874"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.12,0,0.77,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78246"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10559"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63655"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7588"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26832"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78246"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucose is a major source of energy for all cells and is moved into cells with the help of glucose transporters (GLUTs).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is translocated to the plasma membrane in response to insulin in muscle and adipose tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GLUT1","GLUT2","GLUT3","GLUT4","GLUT5"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin facilitates glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissues by promoting the translocation of \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT4\u003C/strong\u003E to the plasma membrane. This process is crucial for maintaining normal blood glucose levels, especially after meals when insulin levels are high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT1\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucose transporter that is responsible for basal glucose uptake and is found in most tissues, including the brain and red blood cells. It is not primarily regulated by insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT2\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the liver, pancreas, and renal tubular cells, and plays a role in glucose sensing and homeostasis. It is not directly involved in insulin-mediated glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT3\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily expressed in neurons and the placenta, where it facilitates high-affinity glucose uptake. It is not regulated by insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT5\u003C/strong\u003E is a fructose transporter found in the small intestine and sperm, and does not play a role in glucose uptake in response to insulin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin stimulates glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue by promoting the translocation of GLUT4 to the plasma membrane.","GLUT4 is the primary glucose transporter responsible for insulin-mediated glucose uptake in these tissues.","Other glucose transporters, such as GLUT1, GLUT2, and GLUT3, have different roles and tissue distributions."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63655"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63655"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T07:30:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T07:32:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10559"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78246"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta